The Boss


Soldier, Broker and C.E.O.









Sign In to E-Mail


Print








Published: January 30, 2010 



I grew up in the Little Italy area of Hartford, in my grandparents’ four-family home. I’m the oldest of six brothers. 


Skip to next paragraph

Enlarge This Image



Sigrid Estrada





JOSEPH J. GRANO JR.
Chairman and C.E.O. of Centurion Holdings, business strategy consultants, New York
AGE 61
HEROINE Margaret Thatcher
HOBBY Gourmet cooking




My immediate family moved several times and arrived in Wethersfield, Conn., my junior year in high school. One day, two friends and I skipped school and went to the beach. One of my friends was driving; in an accident, we were thrown from the car. I was taken to the hospital and released. After I hitchhiked home, blood collected between my retina and my cornea and I became blind in my left eye. I was back in the hospital for two weeks. The day the doctors were to operate, the blood began to recede and my vision returned. I had no other injuries, but I missed most of a semester and was tutored at home the rest of the year. When I returned as a senior, I was elected class president. In my yearbook I was voted most popular. In college, I was intending to be a math teacher. Instead I found myself skipping class and playing pool. After about three months, I said to some friends, “Why don’t we go do our part and fight in Vietnam?” This was 1967. I joined the Army, and after basic and advanced infantry training, I went to officer candidate school and was trained to be a Green Beret officer. I was sent to Panama for two years, then was posted to Vietnam as a captain.I was there eight months when I was ordered on patrol by a new battalion commander. The soldier in front of me tripped on a booby trap, which exploded. Three of us were injured, including me. The man in front lost an eye and a leg. The man behind me ultimately died of a heart wound.After 20 minutes I was airlifted to a field hospital in Chu Lai, then to Okinawa. A month later, I went to the military hospital at Fort Devens, Mass., with multiple broken bones. My left arm had been partly severed in the explosion and was in a long cast. I also had a cast on my left leg. My wife was about to give birth to our first child, but the doctors wouldn’t release me until I could walk. I persuaded some National Guardsmen to help me walk with a cane. I was discharged from the hospital nine days after I arrived, two weeks before our child’s birth. A month after leaving the hospital, I could walk 25 to 30 feet as a result of designing my own physical therapy. My doctors at Fort Devens told me I was doing more for myself than they could do for me. After six months, I was discharged with a 60 percent disability. Doctors told me I’d never be able to lift a milk bottle. They were wrong.While waiting to be discharged, I began selling real estate and saw an ad to become a stockbroker at Merrill Lynch. I limped into its Hartford branch office with my officer efficiency reports. I was sent to New York to take aptitude and psychological tests. The personnel office there advised me to go back to school or gain business experience. But the Hartford local manager recommended me to the New Haven office. I didn’t know anyone in the territory, but I took the job. After three years as a stockbroker, I was asked to head marketing. I rose through the ranks over the next 16 years. I was director of national sales when I left in 1988 to become president of PaineWebber. UBS acquired PaineWebber in 2000; I stayed on as chairman and C.E.O. of UBS PaineWebber until November 2004.I founded Centurion Holdings immediately upon my departure, as I was not then, and am not now, ready to retire. I have anger and sadness seeing financial companies melt down. I won’t forgive some of my friends for concentrating on risky investments and overleveraging. I have an immense conviction that you don’t need to keep up with the Joneses.  As told to Amy Zipkin.



